  "prompt": "What is the difference between indicated horsepower and brake horsepower?",
  "response": "Indicated horsepower (IHP) and brake horsepower (BHP) are two measures of an engine's power output, but they represent different aspects of engine performance:\n\n1. **Indicated Horsepower (IHP):**\n   - **Definition:** Indicated horsepower is the total power developed by the engine's combustion process within the cylinders. It is calculated based on the pressure inside the cylinders and the engine's speed.\n   - **Measurement:** IHP is determined using an **indicator diagram**, which plots the pressure-volume (P-V) cycle of the engine. The area under this curve represents the work done by the engine.\n   - **Includes:** IHP accounts for all the power generated inside the cylinders, including the power lost due to friction, heat, and other inefficiencies within the engine itself.\n\n2. **Brake Horsepower (BHP):**\n   - **Definition:** Brake horsepower is the actual power available at the engine's crankshaft to do useful work. It is the power that is effectively delivered to the drivetrain or other external systems.\n   - **Measurement:** BHP is measured using a **dynamometer**, which applies a load to the engine's output shaft and measures the torque and rotational speed.\n   - **Excludes:** BHP does not include the power lost due to internal engine friction, accessory drives (like the alternator or water pump), or other parasitic losses.\n\n### Key Difference:\nThe main difference between IHP and BHP lies in what they measure:\n- **IHP** represents the total power generated inside the engine cylinders.\n- **BHP** represents the usable power available at the engine's output shaft after accounting for internal losses.\n\n### Relationship:\nBHP is always less than IHP because it factors in the power lost due to friction and other inefficiencies within the engine. The difference between IHP and BHP is often referred to as **friction horsepower (FHP)**:\n\\[ \\text{BHP} = \\text{IHP} - \\text{FHP} \\]\n\nIn summary, IHP is a theoretical measure of the engine's internal power generation, while BHP is a practical measure of the power available for external use.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
